description.plain:
Malcolm Jamaal Davis (b. April 12, 1992), better known by his stage name MadeinTYO (“Made in Tokyo”), is an American rapper from Atlanta, Georgia. He was born in Hawaii but spent most of his youth in Atlanta with his brother 24hrs.

MadeinTYO is best known for his “Uber Everywhere” single of his You Are Forgiven EP. Since the release of that EP, he released Thank You, Mr. Tokyo and 24hrs in Tokyo with 24hrs as well as his track “Skateboard P” with Big Sean.
In August 2017 he released “True’s World”.

He was featured on tracks from 24hrs, A$AP Ferg, KYLE, Chance the Rapper, J Balvin, Ty Dolla $ign, DJ Carnage, Ski Mask the Slump God, the A$AP MOB, Roy Woods and more.

songs.title: Uber Everywhere

description.plain:
MadeinTYO, short for “Made in Tokyo,” is a rapper from Atlanta, Georgia who lived in Tokyo for six years until he graduated high school. He is part of the Private Club collective with brother 24hrs.

During an interview with VICE, MadeinTYO said he recorded this song in his kitchen:

I recorded that song in my kitchen. We were piped up and it was lit. Actually, my mom was in the kitchen, too. My whole crew was there in the kitchen, doing what Private Crew does, and it just came up. “Uber Everywhere” was just a random line that I said and then ran with. I didn’t really feel like it was a song until a day later when I listened to it and said, “Yo, this shit is hard. I think people are really going to mess with it.”

songs.title: Skateboard P

description.plain:
Skateboard P is Pharrell Williams' nickname, which he’s used on songs like “Skateboard P Presents: Show You How to Hustle”.

Pharrell was nicknamed Skateboard P in high school because he was a skateboarder.

MadeinTYO made this banger inspired by Pharrell’s legendary jewelry game.

description.plain:
Travis Scott aka La Flame jumps on the remix for breakout song “Uber Everywhere” by MadeinTYO. The song was originally teased on Travis' Snapchat, “Scottxx,” and later premiered at a night club in Hollywood.

A leaked CDQ version surfaced online on February 15th and was met by a series of “angry tweets” from Travis Scott.
